Diagram 3 (Alive in Pik)
[{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg949\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset129 \'b1\'bc\'b8\'b2;}{\f1\fmodern\fprq2\fcharset129 \'b1\'bc\'b8\'b2;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\lang1042\f0\fs18
\par It is a careless move for white to connect with 1.
\par
\par Black 2 is a good move that applies the proverb stating, "the enemy's key point is your own".
\par
\par If white plays 3, black plays 4 and lives in pik.
\par
\par Instead of 3, if white plays at 4, it just allows black to live with more points when black plays \b\f1 A\b0\f0 .
\par }
